\chapter*{Chapter 14}

\section*{Stochastic block models (SBMs)}

\subsection*{14.1 Introduction}

\textbf{Notes:}

\begin{itemize}
\item The SBM is the simplest model of networks with ``community structure.''

\item No one knows what ``community structure'' is.

\item It is definitely not modularity: sparse ER and random $k$-regular graphs have nonzero modularity, while RHGs have maximum modularity $\to 1$.

\item \textbf{The SBM versus SRGGs in a nutshell:}

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|}
\hline
& SRGG & SBM \\
\hline
$\{x_i\}$ & Positions in space & Community memberships \\
\hline
& \begin{minipage}{0.35\textwidth}
\vspace{0.1cm}
\centering
\textit{Description of a heatmap visualization showing a smooth gradient from blue (bottom-left) to red (top-right), representing probability $p(x,x')$ as a continuous function of spatial positions. The axes are labeled ``Prob.\ Growth'' on both dimensions, with an arrow indicating ``Prob.\ Growth'' pointing to the right.}
\vspace{0.1cm}
\end{minipage}
& \begin{minipage}{0.35\textwidth}
\vspace{0.1cm}
\centering
\textit{Description of a block matrix heatmap showing discrete blocks of blue and orange/red colors, representing probability $p(x,x')$ as a function of community memberships. The matrix has a checkerboard-like pattern with diagonal blocks in one color and off-diagonal blocks in another. The axes are labeled ``Prob.\ Growth'' on both dimensions, with an arrow indicating ``Prob.\ Growth'' pointing to the right.}
\vspace{0.1cm}
\end{minipage}
\\
$p(x,x')$ & & \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\item The degree corrections on top of these homogeneous models are implemented in exactly the same way, via additional hidden variables $\{\lambda_i\}$ or $\{\kappa_i\}$, but the results are different.

\item In real-world networks, the $x$-part of the graphon is most likely a fuzzy mixture like this:

\begin{center}
\textit{Description of a heatmap visualization showing a fuzzy, blurred mixture between the SRGG and SBM patterns. The image displays a gradient from blue to red with some block-like structure, but with smooth transitions rather than sharp boundaries, suggesting a combination of spatial and community-based connection probabilities.}
\end{center}

\item In contrast with LSMs, all the hypercanonical, canonical, and microcanonical versions make sense to consider since all the sufficient statistics are discrete.

\end{itemize}

